## Voice & style rules (don’t drift)

- **No em-dashes in prose** (kept only in: tape labels, marquee track listings, file timestamps, email sign-offs)
- **No triplets** of any kind (period-separated parallel sentences, comma-separated parallel clauses, “X and Y and Z” run-ons doing emphasis, parallel restatement). Real prose moves forward, not in circles.
- **No emphasis-via-rephrasing** (“not X but Y”, “like X, like Y”, “i told her of course. i told her camille has issues”)
- **Lowercase teen voice** for Tegan’s diary, Camille AIM, Hannah AIM. CAPS for emphasis on key words only.
- **Wren’s voice is constructed maturity that cracks at the edges.** She uses sentence capitalization, real punctuation, em-dashes are still banned.
- **Emoticons sprinkled, not decorative.** Tegan: 1 in diary, 1 in early SMS. Camille: escalating in Ch2 AIM. Hannah: most emotional, multiple. Wren and Briar: zero.
- **Canadian spellings** in prose: counsellor, colour. American in code identifiers (ADULT_COUNSELOR).
- **No stereotyped Canadianness** — no Tim Hortons, hockey, “eh”, maple. Specifics: Kettle Lake, U of A, hotmail.com, Halifax.

## Writers’-room discipline

- **Don’t say “the murder.”** It’s “what happened,” “the night of,” “the disappearance.”
- **Don’t pre-commit Wren as killer in own thinking.** Wren is the obvious read; Wren is wrong.
- **Hold ambiguity in Ch1-3 visible text.** No early hints that should belong to later reveals. Subtext is fine; signposting is not.
- **The player should be unsure throughout.** Every chapter can plausibly redirect suspicion. This is a feature.
